Data transformation

In order to make the data clear for efficient visualisation, I would like to make some calculations base on the original data including the change of the life expectancy (life-gap) by using the life expectancy 2020 to substract the one of 2020.

map_world <- map_data("world") 

pop_2020 <- unicef_metadata %>% 
  filter(year==2020)

pop_2000 <- unicef_metadata %>% 
  filter(year==2000)

map_pop_2000 <- full_join(map_world, pop_2000, by = c("region" = "country"))

map_pop_2020 <- full_join(map_world, pop_2020, by = c("region" = "country"))

pop_2020['Life.expectancy.at.birth..total..years.2000'] <-pop_2000['Life.expectancy.at.birth..total..years.']

pop_2020['Life.expectancy.gap'] <-pop_2020['Life.expectancy.at.birth..total..years.']-pop_2020['Life.expectancy.at.birth..total..years.2000']

new_sorted_pop_2020 <- pop_2020[order(pop_2020['Life.expectancy.gap']),]
## Warning in xtfrm.data.frame(x): cannot xtfrm data frames
new_sorted_pop_2020 <- new_sorted_pop_2020 %>% drop_na('Life.expectancy.gap')

new_0_pop_2020 <- new_sorted_pop_2020%>%filter(Life.expectancy.gap < 0 )

countries_life_0 <- (new_0_pop_2020['country'])

Visualize world map chart

After getting the result from calculation, I put it into the map and The world map which showed the change in life expectancy around the world between 2000 and 2020. The chart pointed out that Mexican ranked 1st which mark the biggest decrease in life expectancy in those 20 years

map_sorted_2020 <- full_join(map_world,new_sorted_pop_2020,by=c('region'='country'))

ggplot(data = map_sorted_2020) +
  aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill=Life.expectancy.gap) +
  geom_polygon() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "yellow", high = "red", na.value = "grey") +
  labs(
    title = "Life expectancy gap between countries from 2000 to 2020",
    subtitle = "Countries in grey have no data due to a mismatch with their names",
    x = "Longitude",
    y = "Latitude",
    fill = "Country Life Expectancy Gap Scale"
  ) +
  theme_bw()
